+- When `repo` is set: call `repo.list_refs("refs/heads/work/*")`
+  and classify each ref **by its name**, not by its current SHA.
+  The canonical ref naming pinned by the implementer module is
+  `refs/heads/work/<slug>-<trial_id>` (see
+  `reference/services/web-ui/src/eden_web_ui/routes/implementer.py:69`
+  and the `slug` regex `^[a-z0-9][a-z0-9-]*$` in
+  `spec/v0/02-data-model.md` ┬¦5.1). Classification rule:
+
+  1. Strip the `refs/heads/work/` prefix; split on the **last**
+     `-` to get `(slug, trial_id)` candidates. (`trial_id` is
+     opaque per `02-data-model.md` ┬¦7.1; the slug is already
+     constrained to a-z/0-9/`-`, so the rightmost `-` is the only
+     reliable boundary.)
+  2. Look up `trial = store.read_trial(trial_id)`. Three outcomes:
+     - **Trial exists** and `trial.status` is terminal-and-handled
+       (`error`, `eval_error`, or `success` with `trial_commit_sha`
+       set) **and** the ref's current SHA equals
+       `trial.commit_sha` ŌåÆ **GC-eligible**. Show a delete button.
+     - **Trial exists** but is `starting`, or is `success` without
+       `trial_commit_sha` (integrator hasn't promoted yet), or the
+       ref's SHA does **not** match `trial.commit_sha` ŌåÆ
+       **Not eligible**. List the reason; no delete button. The
+       SHA-mismatch case is the dangerous one ŌĆö it means a third
+       party rewrote the work branch and the operator should
+       investigate before deleting.
+     - **Trial does not exist** (the parsed `trial_id` resolves
+       to no trial) ŌåÆ **Orphan**. Most likely a leftover from a
+       Pre-Phase-1 ref-collision retry that succeeded on a different
+       name, or a manual `git update-ref` outside the system.
+       Show a delete button + "no trial owns this ref" warning.
+     - **Ref name does not parse** (no `-`, or empty slug or
+       trial_id segment) ŌåÆ list as **Unparseable**. No delete
+       button. The operator can clean these up via `git` directly
+       if they know what they are.
 
+  This trial-id-from-name discipline is the trust boundary: a SHA
+  collision between two trials, or a manual ref rewrite, cannot
+  cause us to associate a ref with the wrong trial. The SHA check
+  remains as the eligibility predicate for the parsed-and-known
+  case.
